text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild]]%0a%0a!Accents in My Fair Lady%0a%0a:Author: lauray%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aHow the Cockney accent is perceived as low-class and vulgar in the film, My Fair Lady%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aVideo from My Fair Lady: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EAYUuspQ6BY&ab_channel=shanmugamlakshmanan %0a%0aIn the movie, My Fair Lady, the main character is looked down on because of her accent. The Cockney accent she used was considered a lower class accent and less proper than the standard Received Pronunciation or “Queen’s English” accent.%0a%0aSome key elements of her accent that were criticized was the glottal stopping used in words like “where”, “you”, “going” and “better” which are pronounced with a glottal stop, making better into [be?ə] instead of pronouncing the ‘t’ at the alveolar. Another criticized element of her accent was what is known as the “London vowel shift” where “day” is pronounced as [dæɪ] instead of [deɪ]. %0a%0aThis is part of a dialect of English called the Cockney Dialect which is typically centralized around London, specifically the East End. It is known for having T-glottalization (as shown above with better), and Th-fronting  where /θ/ can become [f] with words like "thin" becoming [fɪn]. These are some of the characteristics that set it apart from the RP accent. It also holds many similarities like being non-rhotic.%0a%0aOne of the characters in the film, Professor Higgins, believes that accent and tone determines people’s prospects in society. He takes on Eliza and is determined to “fix” her and make her into a “proper lady” showing his disdain for her original Cockney accent and that he didn’t think that she had a chance in “society”. This is a more dated example of linguistic discrimination, but shows how accents were taken to signify a person’s place in society as well as the difficulty to move out of that position because of their accent.%0a%0aSources:%0ahttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/My_Fair_Lady_(film)%0ahttp://dialectblog.com/british-accents/%0ahttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cockney%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210501-055658-662150#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Professor Higgins in Linguistics Textbooks %0a-> - rajeev_g%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aFor some additional context, My Fair Lady is based on the play Pygmalion by George Bernard Shaw. Shaw partially based the character of Henry Higgins on several phonetics professors who he knew, but chiefly upon Henry Sweet.%0a%0aInterestingly enough, Sweet was an extremely influential voice in a formative period of linguistics, and his textbooks continue to be used in colleges today [1]. In particular, his work was some of the first to document London speech (received pronunciation), as well as study English apart from Germanic languages.%0a%0aIt's interesting to think that a voice like his, one who influenced the depiction of a patronizing and prescriptivist character, is one that remains relevant to our modern study of linguistics. It probably underscores the need for more conscious understanding and critical analysis of where our knowledge comes from.%0a%0a[1] https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Sweet%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210501-055658-662150#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: D:)%0a(:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild:)
