diff:1619848617:1619319596:=59,73c59%0a%3c #foxbegin 210501-055658-662150#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Professor Higgins in Linguistics Textbooks %0a%3c -> - rajeev_g%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c For some additional context, My Fair Lady is based on the play Pygmalion by George Bernard Shaw. Shaw partially based the character of Henry Higgins on several phonetics professors who he knew, but chiefly upon Henry Sweet.%0a%3c %0a%3c Interestingly enough, Sweet was an extremely influential voice in a formative period of linguistics, and his textbooks continue to be used in colleges today [1]. In particular, his work was some of the first to document London speech (received pronunciation), as well as study English apart from Germanic languages.%0a%3c %0a%3c It's interesting to think that a voice like his, one who influenced the depiction of a patronizing and prescriptivist character, is one that remains relevant to our modern study of linguistics. It probably underscores the need for more conscious understanding and critical analysis of where our knowledge comes from.%0a%3c %0a%3c [1] https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Sweet%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210501-055658-662150#%0a---%0a> %0a
